[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Cross-System Logistics Tracking, Care-Trajectory Modeling, and Conversational Surfacing of Gaps and Next Steps
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Been A Software-Resistant Problem For Decades
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a clinical and operational workflow, has been a phone-and-clinic-and-fax-machine problem for almost all of healthcare's history. The reasons are structural, and most of them are still mostly true today.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first reason is that the relevant data is scattered across systems that were not designed to talk to each other. The patient's primary care physician uses one EHR. The patient's oncologist uses a different EHR at a different organization. The patient's cardiologist uses a third EHR at yet another organization. The patient's pharmacy uses a pharmacy system. The patient's imaging center uses a radiology information system. The patient's insurance has its own claims system. Each of these systems contains some part of the patient's care reality, and almost none of them share data with each other in a usable way without significant effort. Health information exchanges have improved this, the 21st Century Cures Act information-blocking rules and TEFCA have improved this further, FHIR-based APIs have made the technical pieces easier, but the operational reality on the ground for most patients with complex care journeys is that their data lives in seven systems that produce, between them, an incomplete picture even when each individual system is doing its job correctly. <!-- TODO: verify; HIE participation rates and data-availability completeness vary substantially by region, type of provider, and type of data; the 21st Century Cures Act information-blocking provisions and TEFCA framework continue to expand interoperability over time --> A care coordination tool that does not have access to most of these systems is a tool that is missing most of the picture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The second reason is that the structured data that does exist is often messy, incomplete, or inconsistent in ways that matter for care coordination. A "referral" might exist in the EHR as a structured order, or as an unstructured text note in the visit summary, or as nothing at all (the physician told the patient verbally to follow up with a specialist, with no order placed). An "appointment" might exist as a calendar entry in one facility's scheduling system, a calendar entry in another facility's scheduling system, or only in the patient's memory. A "test result" might be in the lab system, in the patient's EHR, in a fax that arrived at the primary care office and was scanned in, or sitting in an inbox waiting for the ordering physician to acknowledge it. A "medication" might be on the medication list in one EHR, on a different medication list in another EHR, on the pharmacy's dispense record, on the patient's pillbox, and the patient might or might not actually be taking it. The structured-data gap between "what is recorded" and "what is true" is, for many patients with complex care journeys, sizable. A care coordination tool that treats the structured data as ground truth without reconciliation is a tool that propagates errors.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The third reason is that the action surface for care coordination is ambiguous in a way that the action surface for, say, prescription refills is not. The refill bot's job is clear: verify the patient, confirm the medication, submit the refill to the pharmacy queue, escalate if clinical review is required. The care coordination assistant's job, when it spots that a patient is overdue for a follow-up appointment, is less clear. Does the assistant schedule the appointment itself? Suggest scheduling to the patient and let the patient call the office? Send a message to the care team? Send a message to the specialist's office? Some combination, depending on the institution, the patient, the type of follow-up, and the institution's workflow? All of the above, in different cases, with the right routing logic? The action surface is institution-specific, often patient-specific, and frequently has to be calibrated against what each provider's office is willing to accept (a primary care office that values active scheduling-on-behalf is different from one that wants the patient to call). Building a care coordination tool that does the right thing in a useful number of cases requires substantial institutional configuration work that the technology alone does not provide.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The fourth reason is that care coordination, when done well, requires a model of "what should happen next" that is harder to encode programmatically than it appears. For a patient with a new cancer diagnosis, "what should happen next" depends on the cancer type, the staging, the treatment pathway the multidisciplinary team has selected, the patient's preferences, the patient's insurance coverage, the patient's distance from various facilities, the patient's social and family situation, and the institution's specific clinical pathway. The pathway might involve, in some configurations: a multidisciplinary tumor-board review, biomarker testing, imaging studies, a port placement, a chemotherapy initiation, supportive-care consults (palliative care, social work, nutrition, financial counseling), serial response-assessment imaging, treatment-related laboratory monitoring, transitions between phases of treatment, post-treatment surveillance, and longitudinal survivorship care. Each of these steps has timing windows, ordering dependencies, and authorization requirements. Encoding this as a "care pathway" the assistant can track is multi-quarter clinical work for each cancer type, and there are many cancer types, and oncology is just one of several care domains a comprehensive assistant has to handle.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first generation of digital care-coordination tools, roughly the early 2000s through the late 2010s, attacked this with workflow software. Care managers got a worklist. Patients got a portal. The tool was a passive view onto the structured data. The clinical evidence for these tools was, broadly, that they were useful for the patients who used them, with substantial demographic and engagement disparities, with limited reach to the patients who needed coordination most. <!-- TODO: verify; patient portal use, care-management workflow software adoption, and outcomes are documented in the health-services research literature; specific findings vary by tool, organization, and population -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The second generation, roughly 2018 to 2023, added some pattern detection and proactive signaling. Care-management platforms started flagging patients who were overdue for screenings, who had recent hospitalizations, who showed risk-score elevation. The tools surfaced gaps to the care-management team. Some platforms added patient-facing nudges. The clinical evidence for the proactive-detection layer was more promising, particularly in capitated arrangements where the care-management staff actually had time to act on the surfaced gaps. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for proactive-detection care-coordination tools includes studies of care-management platforms in ACO and capitated-payer settings, with mixed-to-promising results; specific findings vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape is, again, large language models that can do two things the previous tools could not. The first is the synthesis problem: the assistant can read across the patient's data sources, reason about the trajectory, and produce a coherent picture of where the patient is in their care journey, where they should be next, and what is missing. The second is the conversational interface: the patient can engage with the assistant in plain language, asking questions about their own care, and the assistant can respond with grounded, specific, actionable information. The combination is meaningfully different from a portal that displays structured fields and meaningfully different from an alert system that emails the care team about gaps. The combination, when the underlying integrations are in place and the institutional governance is sound, is something closer to what Linda does at the kitchen table.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "passive view of structured fields" to "synthesizing-and-conversing over a multi-source care trajectory model." The assistant's value is concentrated in five places: the trajectory synthesis (turning fragmented data into a coherent picture), the gap detection (catching the things that are missing or about to fall through), the proactive surfacing (telling the patient or the care team about something they need to know before they would have noticed), the conversational accessibility (lower activation energy than a portal for many populations, including older adults and patients with limited English proficiency), and the operational reach extension (extending the care-coordination workforce's effective coverage from a few percent of the population to a much broader complex-care-journey majority).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care coordination assistant is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (active diagnoses, current providers, current care episodes, pending referrals, scheduled and recent appointments, recent test results, current medications, conversation history with the assistant, stated patient preferences and life context), access to a structured library of clinical pathways and institutional care-coordination protocols (cancer-type-specific pathways, post-surgical pathways, transition-of-care pathways, transplant pathways, complex-diagnostic-workup pathways, multi-condition pathways), and a careful set of tools for retrieving cross-system data, tracking trajectory, detecting gaps, scheduling on behalf of the patient where the institution permits, and escalating to the human care-coordination team when the work requires human judgment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is not one conversation. It is a stream of conversational episodes plus continuous background trajectory monitoring. Patient-initiated conversations cover the most common entry pattern (the patient has a question about their care or a logistical task to accomplish). Assistant-initiated conversations are scheduled per the institution's engagement policy and triggered by gap-detection events. Background monitoring runs continuously, evaluating the patient's trajectory against the relevant pathway and surfacing gaps to the patient or the care team as they emerge.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The assistant's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Onboarding and care-context establishment.** The patient is enrolled in the care-coordination program by their care team or self-enrolls through the patient portal, with documented consent. The first conversation establishes context: who the patient's providers are, what episodes of care are active, what care plans the patient understands themselves to be on, what the patient's preferences are (preferred contact channels, preferred name, language, literacy considerations, family-support context, transportation considerations, work-schedule constraints). The assistant builds an initial care trajectory model from the available structured data, supplemented and corrected by the patient's stated context.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trajectory tracking and gap detection.** The assistant maintains a running model of the patient's care trajectory: pending referrals (with expiration dates), scheduled appointments (with confirmation status), recently-completed appointments (with follow-up status), pending test results (with expected return windows), recently-completed test results (with acknowledgment and action status), pending authorizations (with expiration dates), pending records-transfers between facilities (with confirmation status), active medications across all prescribers (with reconciliation status), pending pathway steps (with timing windows), and overdue items at every level. The trajectory model is reconciled against the institution's pathways for the patient's active care episodes; gaps and overdue items surface as actionable events.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-initiated conversation handling.** The patient asks "when is my next oncology appointment?", "did my MRI results come back?", "do I need a referral to see the cardiologist?", "where am I supposed to go for the pre-op?", "did the records from Memorial Hospital get sent to Dr. Chen's office?". The assistant retrieves the relevant data, synthesizes a plain-language answer, and (where appropriate) suggests a next step.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Proactive engagement with the patient on identified gaps.** The assistant initiates conversations when the trajectory model has identified something the patient should act on (or should be aware of). "Hi David, your follow-up with Dr. Chen is supposed to be scheduled within the next two weeks per the discharge plan, and I haven't seen an appointment booked yet. Want me to check Dr. Chen's available times?" "Hi David, your authorization for the next imaging study is set to expire on March 15. The imaging is scheduled for March 20, which means we need to renew the authorization. Should I message Dr. Chen's office to start the renewal, or would you like to call them yourself?" The proactive engagement is calibrated against the institution's engagement policy, the patient's stated preferences, and engagement-fatigue mitigation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Logistical task support.** Scheduling, rescheduling, requesting records transfers, confirming authorizations, reminding the patient of the next step, walking the patient through a multi-step preparation (pre-procedure prep, lab-prep instructions, fasting requirements, medication-hold instructions). Where the institution permits direct action, the assistant takes the action (using the scheduling bot's infrastructure, the records-request infrastructure, the authorization workflow). Where direct action is not permitted, the assistant prepares the action and routes to the human team or instructs the patient on the next step.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team coordination.** The assistant generates structured handoff messages between providers when the patient is moving between facilities or specialties: "this patient is being seen by Dr. Chen on March 22, the patient's primary care is Dr. Patel at Riverside Clinic, the patient's cardiologist is Dr. Amir at Heart Specialists Group, recent relevant labs and imaging are attached or referenced, here are the relevant medication and allergy reconciliation notes, here are the patient-stated context items relevant to this visit." The handoff messages are reviewed by the care team before delivery, with the assistant providing the structured draft.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-source data reconciliation.** When the assistant detects discrepancies across data sources (medication on the institution's EHR list that does not match the pharmacy's dispense record; appointment in the patient's calendar that does not appear in the scheduling system; test result that has come back to one facility but has not been forwarded to the prescribing physician at another), it surfaces the discrepancy with a proposed reconciliation step.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Escalation to the human care-coordination team.** When the trajectory model shows a high-acuity gap (a critical follow-up that has not happened, a missed-and-not-rescheduled appointment for an episode where missed follow-up has clinical consequences, a pending authorization that is expiring with no clear pathway to renewal, a discrepancy that the assistant cannot reconcile, a patient-reported issue that the assistant is not equipped to handle), the assistant escalates with a structured handoff to a human care coordinator, nurse navigator, social worker, or the primary care physician's office.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Long-term relationship maintenance.** The assistant maintains the relationship across episodes of care over months and years, retaining patient preferences, accumulating life-context disclosures relevant to coordination (caregiver availability, transportation challenges, work-schedule constraints, language preferences, financial constraints), and adapting its engagement to the patient's stated experience.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team reporting and outcome correlation.** The care team has visibility into the assistant's interactions with the patient through structured reports. Outcome correlation against care-gap closure rates, no-show rates, completion rates of recommended care pathways, hospitalization and readmission rates, and patient-reported coordination experience is part of the post-launch operational discipline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat interface, paste in some content about care coordination, and have it help patients. This breaks in several specific ways, each of which has clinical and operational consequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no view of the patient's data across systems.** Without integration to the institution's EHR, external EHRs the patient has authorized data sharing with, claims data, pharmacy data, scheduling systems across facilities, lab systems, radiology systems, and authorization systems, the LLM is operating on whatever the patient typed plus its own training data. The cross-system data integration is the architectural primitive that distinguishes the care coordination assistant from a chatbot.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no model of the patient's care trajectory.** The trajectory model (active care episodes, pathway steps, pending referrals, scheduled appointments, expected follow-up windows, overdue items) is the architectural primitive that allows the assistant to do trajectory tracking and gap detection. Without a structured trajectory model, the LLM is, at best, a question-answering interface over the underlying data, which is a portal with chat instead of a coordination assistant.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model hallucinates appointment times, referral statuses, and test results when grounding is weak.** If the assistant produces "your appointment is on March 22 at 9:30 AM" without strict grounding to the underlying scheduling system, the assistant will sometimes produce a confidently wrong answer, the patient will show up at the wrong time, and the trust the assistant has built will collapse. The grounding discipline for logistical facts is non-negotiable; every logistical claim cites the underlying source with timestamp.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to act vs when to surface.** The action surface is ambiguous, institution-specific, and patient-specific. A generalist LLM defaults to either always taking action ("I'll go ahead and reschedule that for you") or always handing off ("you should call the office to schedule that"). The right behavior depends on the institution's configuration, the patient's stated preferences, the type of action, and the patient's authorization scope. The action-surface routing is encoded in the assistant's policy layer, not left to the LLM's discretion.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no model of clinical pathways.** The pathway library (cancer-type-specific pathways, post-surgical pathways, transition-of-care pathways, transplant pathways, complex-diagnostic-workup pathways) is what the assistant uses to determine "what should happen next" against the patient's actual trajectory. Without the pathway library, the assistant has no reference for gap detection. The pathway library is multi-quarter clinical work; it is also the source of most of the assistant's value.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of staying within scope.** Patients in care-coordination relationships frequently bring up things outside the assistant's scope: clinical questions ("should I take a higher dose?"), benefits questions ("will this be covered?"), triage situations ("I'm having chest pain"), social-determinants concerns ("I can't afford the copay"). The assistant routes each appropriately. A generalist LLM will, by default, attempt to answer all of them, which is a failure mode with consequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has clinical-decision-rule problems.** Most of the care coordination assistant's job is logistics, but logistics intersect with clinical rules in specific places: medication-interaction screening across prescribers, drug-allergy matching at the cross-prescriber level, test-result interpretation at the structured-result level, and trajectory-against-pathway matching. The deterministic clinical-rule tools encapsulate the computation; the LLM does not do this kind of reasoning reliably on its own.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of escalation.** When the patient surfaces "I haven't been able to get my chemo started, the authorization keeps getting denied, and Dr. Chen's office isn't returning my calls," the right response is not "let me give you some tips on appealing authorizations." The right response is to escalate to a human care coordinator with the full context attached. The escalation logic is encoded explicitly with care-team-routing rules.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications across multiple regulatory frameworks.** The care coordination assistant touches PHI from multiple sources, may include PHI from external providers (covered under cross-provider data-sharing agreements), produces operational records subject to HIPAA, may produce records relevant to FDA SaMD positioning depending on configuration, and operates in workflows that intersect with state-specific regulations on patient-care communication.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of cross-provider data trust.** When external EHRs return data via HIE, the data may be incomplete, may be stale, may contain errors, and may not include the institution's own corrections. The assistant has to handle multi-source data with appropriate provenance tracking, conflict-resolution logic, and patient-stated-context reconciliation. A generalist LLM does not do this.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of patient-stated-context as ground truth where structured data is wrong.** The patient often knows things the structured data does not capture: the patient stopped a medication two weeks ago and never told the office, the patient never received the records the office said were transferred, the patient's appointment was rescheduled in a phone call that did not make it into the scheduling system, the patient is no longer using the pharmacy listed in the EHR. The assistant treats the patient's stated context as a credible signal that may take precedence over stale structured data, with appropriate confirmation-and-update mechanics.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of how to interact with care-team workflows.** The care-team-side tooling for receiving handoffs, reviewing the assistant's outputs, taking action on alerts, and providing feedback on the assistant's recommendations is part of the architecture, not a phase-2 enhancement. The integration with the institution's care-management platform, the EHR's task-list functionality, the secure-messaging infrastructure, and the care-team's case-management system is institution-specific work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Assistant Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening with continuous emergency screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, citation grounding, longitudinal-memory governance, behavior-change-stage tracking, crisis-detection. The care coordination assistant adds eight structural commitments those recipes did not have at the same depth.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-system data integration as architectural primitive.** The assistant's value depends on visibility into data across systems. The integration includes the institution's own EHR, external EHRs (where the patient has authorized data sharing through HIE or TEFCA), claims data (where the institution has access), pharmacy data, scheduling systems across facilities, lab systems, radiology systems, and authorization systems. The integration discipline is institution-specific work that has to be built before the assistant is operationally useful.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-trajectory modeling as architectural primitive.** The assistant maintains a structured trajectory model per patient: active care episodes, pathway steps, pending items, scheduled items, completed items, overdue items, expected next steps. The trajectory model is the data structure that allows the assistant to do trajectory tracking and gap detection. The trajectory model is reconciled across data sources and supplemented by patient-stated context.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical-pathway library as institutionally-curated asset.** Each clinical-pathway template (cancer-type-specific pathways, post-surgical pathways, transition-of-care pathways, transplant pathways, complex-diagnostic-workup pathways, multi-condition pathways) is owned by the relevant clinical specialty leadership, version-controlled, reviewed annually. The pathway library is the source of most of the assistant's clinical-relevance and is multi-quarter institutional work to develop and maintain.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Action-surface routing with institution-specific configuration.** The assistant's action surface (what it can do directly vs surface to the patient vs route to the care team vs route to a specific provider's office) is institution-specific, often patient-specific, and frequently patient-stated-preference-specific. The routing logic is encoded in policy, configurable per institution and per workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-source data reconciliation with provenance tracking.** When the assistant produces a logistical claim, it cites the source with timestamp and source-system identifier. When data conflicts across sources, the assistant has explicit reconciliation logic (most-recent-wins, institution-of-record-wins, patient-stated-wins, surface-conflict-to-care-team) per the institution's policy. Provenance tracking is preserved through the audit trail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team integration as first-class capability.** The care team's tooling for receiving handoffs, reviewing the assistant's outputs, taking action on alerts, and providing feedback is part of production scope. The integration with the institution's case-management platform, EHR task-list functionality, secure-messaging infrastructure, and care-team's case-management system is institution-specific work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome correlation against logistical metrics that matter.** The assistant's value is measured against care-gap closure rates, no-show rates, completion rates of recommended care pathways, time-to-follow-up after key events, hospitalization and readmission rates, and patient-reported coordination experience. The outcome-correlation pipeline is multi-quarter post-launch commitment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-provider workflow respect.** The assistant operates in a multi-provider, multi-organization environment. The institutional policies for what the assistant can do at each provider's facility, what records can be moved between facilities, what authorizations are needed for cross-facility actions, and what the receiving facility's preferred handoff format is are institution-specific configuration that has to be built into the assistant's behavior. Acting outside the cross-provider workflow contract damages relationships the institution depends on.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Care-Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care coordination specifically harder than the previous patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The integration surface is the broadest in the chapter.** The assistant's value is bounded above by the breadth and quality of its data integrations. Building a care-coordination assistant that only sees the institution's own EHR data is the most common ambitious-failure pattern; the patients with the most complex care journeys are precisely the ones whose care happens across multiple organizations. Investing seriously in HIE participation, TEFCA-aligned data sharing, and per-vendor integration with the major external EHRs in the region is the largest pre-deployment cost.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Data quality is the second-largest constraint.** Even with the integrations in place, the data is messy. Duplicate medication entries, stale appointment records, referrals without expiration tracking, test results without acknowledgment status, authorization records without renewal triggers. The assistant has to handle messy data without amplifying the messiness. Per-data-source quality monitoring, reconciliation rules, and conflict-resolution logic are part of the architecture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The action surface is institution-specific in ways that do not generalize.** What the assistant should do when it detects an overdue follow-up varies by institution, by provider's office, by patient, and by type of follow-up. There is no single right answer. The institutional configuration work to define the action surface for each common pattern is multi-quarter and frequently underestimated.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The patient population is heterogeneous.** Some patients have one complex episode (a new cancer diagnosis being managed); some have multiple chronic conditions plus an episodic concern; some have transitions of care (recent discharge, recent procedure); some have ongoing surveillance (post-cancer survivorship, post-transplant). The assistant has to handle the range without producing the wrong protocol for any of them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Family caregivers are common and consequential.** Linda is the most important member of David's care team, and many patients with complex care journeys have a family-caregiver counterpart. The assistant has to support family-caregiver involvement (proxy access, authorization to discuss, family-caregiver-as-conversational-partner) per institutional policy and per the patient's documented authorization. Failing to support family-caregiver involvement is a meaningful equity issue (older adults, patients with cognitive impairment, patients with limited English proficiency disproportionately rely on family-caregiver support).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trust is hard to earn and easy to lose.** A care coordination assistant that produces a wrong appointment time, a wrong referral status, a wrong medication list, or a missing critical follow-up will lose patient and care-team trust quickly. The grounding discipline, the data-quality monitoring, and the conservative-bias defaults are not just architectural niceties; they are trust-preservation requirements. Per-cohort monitoring is essential; aggregate accuracy metrics hide failure modes that destroy trust in specific patient populations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-coordination is a workforce-augmentation product, not a replacement product.** The assistant's job is to extend the human care-coordination workforce's reach. The institution still has nurse care coordinators, nurse navigators, social workers, clinic managers, and primary care office staff. The assistant's relationship with these roles is collaborative; the assistant handles the routine logistics, the humans handle the cases that need judgment, the assistant escalates when warranted, the humans review the assistant's outputs as part of normal workflow. Building the assistant without active participation from the human care-coordination workforce produces an assistant the workforce does not trust, which is an expensive failure mode.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-organization politics are real.** When the assistant operates across organizational boundaries (the patient's primary care is at one organization, the specialist is at another, the lab is at a third), the assistant's behavior is constrained by cross-organization data-sharing agreements, by what each receiving organization's office is willing to accept (an automated request for records vs a personal call from a care coordinator), and by the cross-organizational politics of who owns the patient. The institutional governance for the assistant has to navigate this carefully.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity considerations are central.** The patients with the most complex care journeys are often the patients with the least access to and comfort with digital tools. A care coordination assistant that only reaches digitally-engaged patients misses the patients who need coordination most. Multi-channel deployment (SMS-first as a dominant channel, voice-channel option, family-caregiver involvement) is essential. Multi-language deployment with validated translations is essential. Per-cohort monitoring with explicit equity focus is essential.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome demonstration is multi-year.** The assistant's effect on care-gap closure rates may show up in quarters; the effect on hospitalization and readmission rates shows up over twelve to twenty-four months; the effect on broader population-health metrics (mortality, cost-of-care) shows up over years. Institutions building this with quarterly-impact expectations will be disappointed; institutions willing to invest at the right time horizon can demonstrate genuinely meaningful outcomes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for some workflows.** Several mature care-management platforms offer care-coordination features for specific populations (complex case management, oncology navigation, transitions of care). Most major institutions run a hybrid: licensed platforms for specific workflows, in-house thin-coordination layer for the cross-cutting conversational interface and trajectory model, integration with the institution's care-management staff workflows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Regulatory positioning is condition-specific.** Care coordination for post-acute transitions, for cancer-treatment pathways, for transplant work-up, and for complex medication-management each has distinct regulatory considerations. The institutional regulatory team is involved from architectural design and reviews each major use-case extension.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **TEFCA participation is expanding.** The Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement provides a national framework for patient-record exchange across providers. <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA was launched in 2022 by ONC with phased onboarding of Qualified Health Information Networks; specific participation rates and operational maturity continue to evolve --> A care coordination assistant operating in 2026 has access to a meaningfully better cross-provider data picture than one operating in 2019 had, and the trend is positive. The assistant's architecture should anticipate continued expansion in cross-provider data availability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR-based integrations are the dominant pattern for new builds.** The 21st Century Cures Act information-blocking rules and the HL7 FHIR R4 standard have made FHIR-based integration the default for new EHR integrations. <!-- TODO: verify; FHIR R4 adoption has expanded substantially since 2020 with major EHR vendors providing FHIR APIs and SMART on FHIR support; specific adoption levels vary --> The CarePlan, Goal, ServiceRequest, Appointment, Encounter, Observation, MedicationStatement, AllergyIntolerance, Condition, and Communication FHIR resources are the natural primitives for a care coordination assistant.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-management platforms are consolidating around AI-augmented workflows.** Several major care-management platform vendors have integrated AI-assisted features for gap detection, patient outreach, and documentation. The build-vs-buy boundary is shifting; institutions are building thin coordination-conversational layers that integrate with vendor care-management platforms rather than replacing them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle care coordination well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from previous chapter 11 recipes maps cleanly to care coordination. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve the patient's care episodes, retrieve scheduled appointments, retrieve referral status, retrieve recent test results, retrieve medication reconciliation, retrieve authorization status, retrieve clinical pathways, surface gaps, schedule on behalf of the patient where authorized, escalate to the human care-coordination team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid AI-plus-human care coordination is the dominant production pattern.** AI assistant for the broad care-coordination majority, with human care-coordinator availability for high-acuity cases, complex multi-system disputes, social-determinants concerns, and patient-requested human contact. The economics work because the AI assistant handles the routine logistics while the human team focuses where judgment is needed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome demonstration is mixed but trending positive for hybrid models.** Studies of care-coordination programs with technology augmentation have shown improvements in care-gap closure rates, no-show rates, completion rates of recommended care pathways, hospitalization and readmission rates, and patient-reported coordination experience for engaged participants, with the magnitude of effect varying by program design, condition mix, and population. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for technology-augmented care coordination includes studies of programs in ACO and capitated-payer settings, transitions-of-care interventions, and oncology navigation programs; specific outcome figures vary by study -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity considerations are a major area of attention.** Studies of digital health tools have documented variability in adoption, engagement, and outcomes by patient demographics. The risk that a care coordination assistant reaches the patients who need it least and misses the patients who need it most is real. Per-cohort monitoring is essential, and the institutional commitment to equity is reviewed by compliance and patient-experience teams.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
